<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06051m"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06051m">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06051m"> 51(m)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Doll (she)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A l&apos;&acirc;ge de deux ans, &eacute;crit une dame &agrave; J. Sully, L. commen&ccedil;a &agrave; parler de son cheval de bois favori, Dobbin, comme si c&apos;&eacute;tait une cr&eacute;ature vivante: &hellip; Si quelqu&apos;un employait, en parlant de son cheval, le pronom <i>it</i> (cela) r&eacute;serv&eacute; aux objets inanim&eacute;s, il se mettait imm&eacute;diatement dans une violente col&egrave;re et criait avec indignation: &ldquo;<i>It</i>, vous ne devez pas dire <i>it</i>, <mark>vous devez dire <i>he</i></mark>&nbsp;(il).&rdquo; <font color="green">[At the age of two, wrote a lady to J. Sully, L. began to talk about his favorite wooden horse, Dobbin, as if it were a living creature: ... If anyone used, speaking of his horse, the pronoun it&nbsp;(it) reserved for inanimate objects, he immediately put himself in a violent anger and shouted with indignation: &ldquo;It, you do not have to say it, you must say he.&rdquo;]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 91-2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
